properties.description: Birmingham Selly Oak Weather posted a photo: IMAGE: View NW at 09:33BST WEATHER REPORT from Birmingham Selly Oak Weather Station at 09:20BST: Significant change in the weather with approach of complex low pressure area from the west, situated to west of Ireland 994mb at 01:00BST today. Passage of associated frontal systems across Britain over the past 24 hours bringing cloud and showery rain. Visibility good. Current air temperature 14.4°C; maximum air temperature yesterday 21.9°C at 12:28BST; minimum air temperature 11.9°C at 07:13BST today. Grass minimum temperature 11.3°C. Wind direction from S but variable between S and W; mean wind speed 12.6km/h (Force 3); maximum wind speed yesterday 24.5km/h (Force 4) from SSE at 17:28BST yesterday. Rainfall for the past 24 hours 5.5mm. Atmospheric pressure 1002mb, falling from 1017mb over the past 46 hours. Flickr viewers! To find out more about Selly Park, Birmingham, UK, please take a look at our neighbourhood website at: www.sellyparksouth.org.uk

properties.title: Smile Number 1 of 366
properties.description: andyreevo posted a photo: This is my commuter bike, it makes me smile everyday and may feature more than once during this project. I was sheltering from a random downpour on my way home and thought this was a great scene. On the 6th of July 2010 my elder brother sadly passed away suddenly. He left me some money with which I bought my first decent camera so I have decided to start a 366 project in memory of him. Anyone who knew him knows that he always had a smile on his face and he bought a great deal of happiness to a lot of people. So in his honour I am going to attempt to take a picture everyday which makes me smile. When you are grieving the loss of someone, sometimes smiling is the most difficult thing to do but also one of the best things to do. I don't think every picture will be fantastic but hopefully they may make you smile as well. And hopefully I'll learn lots along the way.

properties.title: Pogus Caesar / Benjamin Zephaniah: Birmingham, UK
properties.description: Pogus Caesar / OOM Gallery Archive posted a photo: © Pogus Caesar / OOM Gallery Archive 2011www.oomgallery.co.uk Sparkbrook Pride by Pogus Caesar Birmingham based photographer and film maker Pogus Caesar launches a new book during The Birmingham Book Festival in October. The publication was specially commissioned by Be Birmingham and published by OOM Gallery Archive and Punch. 'Sparkbrook Pride' consists of 70 black and white photographs featuring residents of Sparkbrook, Birmingham, UK – where Pogus grew up, all taken with his trademark Canon Sureshot 35mm camera. The book also has a foreword written by poet, author and playright Benjamin Zephaniah and an introduction by Paris based photographer Nigel Dickinson. In the foreword Zephaniah says "I love the 'rawness' of these photos, they have a sense of place, yet nothing is staged, and the only information Pogus gives us about those featured is how they define themselves, nothing more. We need no more. So people, it is down to us to piece together the rest of this multicultural puzzle". Last autumn Caesar regularly visited Sparkbrook, and the striking images in 'Sparkbrook Pride' are the result. Documenting the diverse individuals who live and work in the area, the book features both the long standing residents from the West Indies, Ireland, India and Pakistan and the more recent additions to the community from Somalia, Sudan, Malawi and Afghanistan, celebrating the rich cultural mix that defines the area. Pogus Caesar is a leading social documentary photographer. He has recorded key moments in Birmingham's recent history including the Bullring regeneration, Birmingham tornado and the Handsworth riots. According to Caesar "Simplicity is best when working with diverse communities; I prefer to photograph the changing world as it unfolds around me". MADE in association with OOM Gallery Archive and Punch will launch Sparkbrook Pride on 10th October 2011 during The Birmingham Book Festival. Book details: Paperback, perfect bound, 160 pages, 70 black and white photographs, 11.6 x 8.2 x 0.8 inches. ISBN: 978-0-9566741-1-1

properties.title: Photographers Roam Wild
properties.description: Shotslot posted a photo: One of the 293 (!?) shots I took yesterday at the Fatherfest Birmingham meet-up. I had a great day and everyone was so much fun! Expect to see lots more of these images...well when I get my arse into editing them so could be a couple of months! Meanwhile, I have a collection of out-take shots from the meet - maybe I could finance that next lens with an Auction!
